variable (Human Horse HasHooves : U → Prop)

-- The statement under evaluation: "Some humans are horses."
def SomeHumansAreHorses : Prop := ∃ x : U, Human x ∧ Horse x

-- Premises:
-- 1) All horses have hooves.
-- 2) No humans have hooves.
-- Conclusion: From these, it follows that no human is a horse, hence
--             "Some humans are horses" is false.
theorem no_human_is_horse
  (all_horses_have_hooves : ∀ x : U, Horse x → HasHooves x)
  (no_humans_have_hooves : ∀ x : U, Human x → ¬ HasHooves x) :
  ¬ SomeHumansAreHorses U Human Horse := by
  intro h
  -- h : ∃ x, Human x ∧ Horse x
  apply Exists.elim h
  intro x hx
  -- hx : Human x ∧ Horse x
  have hxHuman : Human x := And.left hx
  have hxHorse : Horse x := And.right hx
  have hh : HasHooves x := all_horses_have_hooves x hxHorse
  have nh : ¬ HasHooves x := no_humans_have_hooves x hxHuman
  exact nh hh

constant Symphony9 : U
constant ViennaMusicSociety : U

constant Composer : U → Prop
constant Wrote : U → U → Prop
constant Premiered : U → U → Prop
constant Orchestra : U → Prop
constant Leads : U → U → Prop
constant Conductor : U → Prop

axiom composers_write : ∀ x : U, Composer x → ∃ y : U, MusicPiece y ∧ Wrote x y

axiom vms_premiered : Premiered ViennaMusicSociety Symphony9

  ∀ x o : U, Leads x o → Orchestra o → Conductor x

    beethoven_leads_vms vms_is_orchestra

-/

-- Abstract formalization of the problem
universe u

section
variable {Person : Type u}
variable {Nice Mean Grumpy AnimalLover PetOwner : Person → Prop}
variable {Tom : Person}

-- Premises (as parameters)
-- h1: No one nice to animals is also mean to animals.
-- h2: Some grumpy people are mean to animals.
-- h3: All animal lovers are nice to animals.
-- h4: All pet owners love animals.
-- h5: Tom is a pet owner.

-- A derived consequence: Tom is not mean to animals.
theorem tom_not_mean
  (h1 : ∀ x, Nice x → ¬ Mean x)
  (h2 : ∃ x, Grumpy x ∧ Mean x)
  (h3 : ∀ x, AnimalLover x → Nice x)
  (h4 : ∀ x, PetOwner x → AnimalLover x)
  (h5 : PetOwner Tom) :
  ¬ Mean Tom := by
  have hAL : AnimalLover Tom := h4 Tom h5
  have hNice : Nice Tom := h3 Tom hAL
  exact h1 Tom hNice
end

-- A concrete countermodel showing the conclusion "Tom is grumpy" does not follow from the premises.
namespace CounterModel

inductive Person : Type
| Tom
| Alice
deriving DecidableEq

open Person

def Nice : Person → Prop
| Tom => True
| Alice => False

def Mean : Person → Prop
| Tom => False
| Alice => True

def Grumpy : Person → Prop
| Tom => False
| Alice => True

def AnimalLover : Person → Prop
| Tom => True
| Alice => False

def PetOwner : Person → Prop
| Tom => True
| Alice => False

-- Verify the premises in this model.
theorem ax1 : ∀ x, Nice x → ¬ Mean x := by
  intro x hx hmean
  cases x with
  | Tom =>
    -- Mean Tom = False
    simpa [Mean] using hmean
  | Alice =>
    -- Nice Alice = False, contradiction from hx
    simpa [Nice] using hx

theorem ax2 : ∃ x, Grumpy x ∧ Mean x := by
  refine ⟨Alice, ?_⟩
  have hG : Grumpy Alice := by simpa [Grumpy]
  have hM : Mean Alice := by simpa [Mean]
  exact And.intro hG hM

theorem ax3 : ∀ x, AnimalLover x → Nice x := by
  intro x hx
  cases x with
  | Tom =>
    exact True.intro
  | Alice =>
    cases hx

theorem ax4 : ∀ x, PetOwner x → AnimalLover x := by
  intro x hx
  cases x with
  | Tom =>
    exact True.intro
  | Alice =>
    cases hx

theorem ax5 : PetOwner Tom := by
  exact True.intro

-- In this model, Tom is not grumpy.
theorem tom_not_grumpy : ¬ Grumpy Tom := by
  intro h
  simpa [Grumpy] using h

end CounterModel

-- Another model showing that the negation "Tom is not grumpy" is also not derivable.
-- Here the premises hold and Tom IS grumpy.
namespace ModelTomGrumpy

inductive Person : Type
| Tom
| Alice
deriving DecidableEq

open Person

def Nice : Person → Prop
| Tom => True
| Alice => False

def Mean : Person → Prop
| Tom => False
| Alice => True

def Grumpy : Person → Prop
| Tom => True
| Alice => True

def AnimalLover : Person → Prop
| Tom => True
| Alice => False

def PetOwner : Person → Prop
| Tom => True
| Alice => False

theorem ax1 : ∀ x, Nice x → ¬ Mean x := by
  intro x hx hmean
  cases x with
  | Tom =>
    simpa [Mean] using hmean
  | Alice =>
    simpa [Nice] using hx

theorem ax2 : ∃ x, Grumpy x ∧ Mean x := by
  refine ⟨Alice, ?_⟩
  have hG : Grumpy Alice := by simpa [Grumpy]
  have hM : Mean Alice := by simpa [Mean]
  exact And.intro hG hM

theorem ax3 : ∀ x, AnimalLover x → Nice x := by
  intro x hx
  cases x with
  | Tom =>
    exact True.intro
  | Alice =>
    cases hx

theorem ax4 : ∀ x, PetOwner x → AnimalLover x := by
  intro x hx
  cases x with
  | Tom =>
    exact True.intro
  | Alice =>
    cases hx

theorem ax5 : PetOwner Tom := by
  exact True.intro

-- In this model, Tom is grumpy.
theorem tom_grumpy : Grumpy Tom := by
  simpa [Grumpy]

end ModelTomGrumpy

constant Person : Type
constant Organization : Type
constant Work : Type

constant Beethoven : Person
constant ViennaMusicSociety : Organization
constant SymphonyNo9 : Work

constant MusicPiece : Work -> Prop
constant Composer : Person -> Prop
constant writes : Person -> Work -> Prop
constant premiered : Organization -> Work -> Prop
constant Orchestra : Organization -> Prop
constant leads : Person -> Organization -> Prop
constant Conductor : Person -> Prop

-- Facts from the context
axiom sym9_is_music_piece : MusicPiece SymphonyNo9
axiom composers_write_music_pieces :
  forall (p : Person) (w : Work), Composer p -> MusicPiece w -> writes p w
axiom beethoven_wrote_sym9 : writes Beethoven SymphonyNo9
axiom vms_premiered_sym9 : premiered ViennaMusicSociety SymphonyNo9
axiom vms_is_orchestra : Orchestra ViennaMusicSociety
axiom beethoven_leads_vms : leads Beethoven ViennaMusicSociety
axiom orchestras_are_led_by_conductors :
  forall (o : Organization), Orchestra o -> forall (p : Person), leads p o -> Conductor p

-- Derived consequence: Beethoven is a conductor
theorem beethoven_is_conductor : Conductor Beethoven :=
  orchestras_are_led_by_conductors ViennaMusicSociety vms_is_orchestra Beethoven beethoven_leads_vms

-- Therefore, it is not the case that Beethoven is not a conductor
theorem not_beethoven_not_conductor : Not (Not (Conductor Beethoven)) :=
  fun h => h beethoven_is_conductor

<lean>
-- We formalize the problem in Lean 4 and prove the desired statement.

universe u
constant Entity : Type u

-- Predicates and relations
constant MountainRange : Entity → Prop
constant InNM : Entity → Prop
constant InTX : Entity → Prop
constant Visited : Entity → Entity → Prop
constant LocatedIn : Entity → Entity → Prop
constant Donated : Entity → Prop

-- Constants for entities
constant Picuris : Entity
constant Juan : Entity
constant Harding : Entity

-- Axioms from the textual context
axiom hMR : MountainRange Picuris
axiom hOr : InNM Picuris ∨ InTX Picuris
axiom hVisited : Visited Juan Picuris
axiom hLoc : LocatedIn Harding Picuris
axiom hDon : Donated Harding
axiom hNoTxDonMine :
  ∀ x, MountainRange x ∧ InTX x → ¬ ∃ m, LocatedIn m x ∧ Donated m

-- Claim: Juan visited a mountain range in New Mexico.
theorem claim : ∃ r, MountainRange r ∧ InNM r ∧ Visited Juan r := by
  -- There exists a donated mine located in Picuris (Harding)
  have hex : ∃ m, LocatedIn m Picuris ∧ Donated m :=
    ⟨Harding, And.intro hLoc hDon⟩
  -- Picuris cannot be in Texas, otherwise it would contradict hNoTxDonMine
  have hNotTx : ¬ InTX Picuris := by
    intro hTx
    have hContra := hNoTxDonMine Picuris ⟨hMR, hTx⟩
    exact hContra hex
  -- From (InNM Picuris ∨ InTX Picuris) and ¬ InTX Picuris, deduce InNM Picuris
  have hNM : InNM Picuris := by
    cases hOr with
    | inl hnm => exact hnm
    | inr htx => exact False.elim (hNotTx htx)
  -- Conclude the existence of a mountain range in NM that Juan visited
  exact ⟨Picuris, And.intro hMR (And.intro hNM hVisited)⟩
</lean>
ANSWER: True

lean_code:
-- Fixed Lean 4 code without universe issues

constant Entity : Type

-- Predicates and relations
constant MountainRange : Entity → Prop
constant InNM : Entity → Prop
constant InTX : Entity → Prop
constant Visited : Entity → Entity → Prop
constant LocatedIn : Entity → Entity → Prop
constant Donated : Entity → Prop

-- Constants for entities
constant Picuris : Entity
constant Juan : Entity
constant Harding : Entity

-- Axioms from the textual context
axiom hMR : MountainRange Picuris
axiom hOr : InNM Picuris ∨ InTX Picuris
axiom hVisited : Visited Juan Picuris
axiom hLoc : LocatedIn Harding Picuris
axiom hDon : Donated Harding
axiom hNoTxDonMine :
  ∀ x, MountainRange x ∧ InTX x → ¬ ∃ m, LocatedIn m x ∧ Donated m

-- Claim: Juan visited a mountain range in New Mexico.
theorem claim : ∃ r, MountainRange r ∧ InNM r ∧ Visited Juan r := by
  -- There exists a donated mine located in Picuris (Harding)
  have hex : ∃ m, LocatedIn m Picuris ∧ Donated m :=
    ⟨Harding, And.intro hLoc hDon⟩
  -- Picuris cannot be in Texas, otherwise it would contradict hNoTxDonMine
  have hNotTx : ¬ InTX Picuris := by
    intro hTx
    have hContra := hNoTxDonMine Picuris ⟨hMR, hTx⟩
    exact hContra hex
  -- From (InNM Picuris ∨ InTX Picuris) and ¬ InTX Picuris, deduce InNM Picuris
  have hNM : InNM Picuris := by
    cases hOr with
    | inl hnm => exact hnm
    | inr htx => exact False.elim (hNotTx htx)
  -- Conclude the existence of a mountain range in NM that Juan visited
  exact ⟨Picuris, And.intro hMR (And.intro hNM hVisited)⟩

<lean>
universe u

-- Domain of discourse
constant U : Type u

-- Predicates
constant Style : U → Prop
constant Zaha : U → Prop
constant Kelly : U → Prop
constant Adores : U → Prop          -- Max adores this item
constant Interesting : U → Prop
constant Brutalist : U → Prop
constant Building : U → Prop
constant Evocative : U → Prop
constant Dreamy : U → Prop
constant Design : U → Prop
constant ByMax : U → Prop           -- item is a design by Max

-- Premises translated from the text
axiom P1 : ∀ x : U, Style x ∧ Zaha x ∧ Adores x → Interesting x
axiom P2 : ∀ x : U, Brutalist x ∧ Building x ∧ Adores x → ¬ Interesting x
axiom P3 : ∀ x : U, Style x ∧ Adores x → Zaha x ∨ Kelly x
axiom P4 : ∀ x : U, Style x ∧ Kelly x ∧ Adores x → Evocative x
axiom P5 : ∀ x : U, Style x ∧ Kelly x ∧ Adores x → Dreamy x
axiom P6 : ∀ x : U, Design x ∧ ByMax x ∧ Adores x ∧ Interesting x → Brutalist x ∧ Building x ∧ Evocative x

-- Target statement: “A design by Max is a brutalist building.”
-- Interpreted as an existential claim:
def Target : Prop := ∃ x : U, Design x ∧ ByMax x ∧ Brutalist x ∧ Building x

-- A derived lemma showing a consistency consequence of the premises:
-- If there were an adored-by-Max interesting design by Max, it would yield a contradiction.
theorem no_adored_byMax_interesting :
  ∀ x : U, Design x ∧ ByMax x ∧ Adores x ∧ Interesting x → False := by
  intro x hx
  have hD : Design x := hx.left
  have hRest1 : ByMax x ∧ Adores x ∧ Interesting x := hx.right
  have hBM : ByMax x := hRest1.left
  have hRest2 : Adores x ∧ Interesting x := hRest1.right
  have hA : Adores x := hRest2.left
  have hI : Interesting x := hRest2.right
  have hBBE : Brutalist x ∧ Building x ∧ Evocative x := P6 x ⟨hD, hBM, hA, hI⟩
  have hBr : Brutalist x := hBBE.left
  have hBEv : Building x ∧ Evocative x := hBBE.right
  have hBld : Building x := hBEv.left
  have hNotI : ¬ Interesting x := P2 x ⟨hBr, hBld, hA⟩
  exact hNotI hI

lean_code:
universe u

-- Domain of discourse
constant U : Type u

-- Predicates
constant Style : U → Prop
constant Zaha : U → Prop
constant Kelly : U → Prop
constant Adores : U → Prop          -- Max adores this item
constant Interesting : U → Prop
constant Brutalist : U → Prop
constant Building : U → Prop
constant Evocative : U → Prop
constant Dreamy : U → Prop
constant Design : U → Prop
constant ByMax : U → Prop           -- item is a design by Max

-- Premises translated from the text
axiom P1 : ∀ x : U, Style x ∧ Zaha x ∧ Adores x → Interesting x
axiom P2 : ∀ x : U, Brutalist x ∧ Building x ∧ Adores x → ¬ Interesting x
axiom P3 : ∀ x : U, Style x ∧ Adores x → Zaha x ∨ Kelly x
axiom P4 : ∀ x : U, Style x ∧ Kelly x ∧ Adores x → Evocative x
axiom P5 : ∀ x : U, Style x ∧ Kelly x ∧ Adores x → Dreamy x
axiom P6 : ∀ x : U, Design x ∧ ByMax x ∧ Adores x ∧ Interesting x → Brutalist x ∧ Building x ∧ Evocative x

-- Target statement: “A design by Max is a brutalist building.”
-- Interpreted as an existential claim:
def Target : Prop := ∃ x : U, Design x ∧ ByMax x ∧ Brutalist x ∧ Building x

-- A derived lemma: an adored-by-Max interesting design by Max leads to contradiction with P2 and P6.
theorem no_adored_byMax_interesting :
  ∀ x : U, Design x ∧ ByMax x ∧ Adores x ∧ Interesting x → False := by
  intro x hx
  -- Extract components
  have hD : Design x := hx.left
  have hRest1 : ByMax x ∧ Adores x ∧ Interesting x := hx.right
  have hBM : ByMax x := hRest1.left
  have hRest2 : Adores x ∧ Interesting x := hRest1.right
  have hA : Adores x := hRest2.left
  have hI : Interesting x := hRest2.right
  -- From P6, such an x would be Brutalist and a Building (and Evocative)
  have hBBE : Brutalist x ∧ Building x ∧ Evocative x := P6 x ⟨hD, hBM, hA, hI⟩
  have hBr : Brutalist x := hBBE.left
  have hBEv : Building x ∧ Evocative x := hBBE.right
  have hBld : Building x := hBEv.left
  -- From P2, anything Brutalist, Building, and adored is not Interesting
  have hNotI : ¬ Interesting x := P2 x ⟨hBr, hBld, hA⟩
  exact hNotI hI

section

constant Person : Type
constant Nice : Person → Prop
constant Mean : Person → Prop
constant Grumpy : Person → Prop
constant Lover : Person → Prop
constant Owner : Person → Prop
constant Tom : Person

-- Axioms from the textual context
axiom H1 : forall x : Person, Nice x → Mean x → False                 -- No one nice to animals is also mean to animals
axiom H2 : Exists (fun x : Person => And (Grumpy x) (Mean x))          -- Some grumpy people are mean to animals
axiom H3 : forall x : Person, Lover x → Nice x                         -- All animal lovers are nice to animals
axiom H4 : forall x : Person, Owner x → Lover x                        -- All pet owners love animals
axiom H5 : Owner Tom                                                   -- Tom is a pet owner

-- Useful derived facts about Tom
lemma loverTom : Lover Tom :=
  H4 Tom H5

lemma niceTom : Nice Tom :=
  H3 Tom loverTom

lemma notMeanTom : Mean Tom → False :=
  H1 Tom niceTom

lemma antecedentTrue : And (Grumpy Tom) (Mean Tom) → False :=
  fun h => notMeanTom h.right

lemma notConclusion : And (Grumpy Tom → False) (Lover Tom → False) → False :=
  fun h => h.right loverTom

-- The statement to assess:
def Statement : Prop :=
  (And (Grumpy Tom) (Mean Tom) → False) → And (Grumpy Tom → False) (Lover Tom → False)

-- We prove the negation of the statement
theorem Statement_false : Statement → False := by
  intro himp
  have concl : And (Grumpy Tom → False) (Lover Tom → False) := himp antecedentTrue
  exact notConclusion concl

end

-- We formalize the entities and predicates
universe u

constant Entity : Type u

constant Onate : Entity
constant PM : Entity        -- Picuris Mountains
constant HPM : Entity       -- Harding Pegmatite Mine

constant MountainRange : Entity → Prop
constant InTexas : Entity → Prop
constant InNewMexico : Entity → Prop
constant Mine : Entity → Prop
constant Donated : Entity → Prop
constant LocatedIn : Entity → Entity → Prop
constant Visited : Entity → Entity → Prop

-- Axioms extracted from the textual context
axiom ax1 : MountainRange PM
axiom ax2 : InNewMexico PM ∨ InTexas PM
axiom ax3 : Visited Onate PM
axiom ax4 : Mine HPM
axiom ax5 : LocatedIn HPM PM
axiom ax6 : Donated HPM
axiom ax7 : ∀ r, (MountainRange r ∧ InTexas r) → ¬ ∃ m, Mine m ∧ LocatedIn m r ∧ Donated m
-- "There are no mountain ranges in Texas that have mines that have been donated."

-- From the donation of HPM located in PM and ax7, PM cannot be in Texas.
lemma not_in_texas_PM : ¬ InTexas PM := by
  intro htx
  have ex : ∃ m, Mine m ∧ LocatedIn m PM ∧ Donated m := by
    exact ⟨HPM, And.intro ax4 (And.intro ax5 ax6)⟩
  have hnot := ax7 PM (And.intro ax1 htx)
  exact hnot ex

-- Hence, by the disjunction "in New Mexico or Texas", PM is in New Mexico.
lemma in_new_mexico_PM : InNewMexico PM := by
  have h := ax2
  cases h with
  | inl hnm => exact hnm
  | inr htx => exact False.elim (not_in_texas_PM htx)

-- The queried statement:
-- "Juan de Onate visited a mountain range in Texas."
def Claim : Prop := ∃ r, MountainRange r ∧ InTexas r ∧ Visited Onate r

-- We can show PM is not a witness, but we cannot derive Claim or its negation from the axioms.
lemma PM_not_witnesses_Claim : ¬ (MountainRange PM ∧ InTexas PM ∧ Visited Onate PM) := by
  intro h
  exact not_in_texas_PM h.2.1
</lean>

<lean>
-- We model the domain of "designs" (or items) as a type U.
variable (U : Type)

-- Predicates on U:
-- Adores: Max adores the item
-- Zaha: the item is a Zaha Hadid design style
-- Kelly: the item is a Kelly Wearstler design style
-- Brutalist: the item is a brutalist building
-- Interesting: the item has interesting geometries
-- Evocative: the item is evocative
-- Dreamy: the item is dreamy
variables
  (Adores Zaha Kelly Brutalist Interesting Evocative Dreamy : U → Prop)

-- Assumptions translated from the textual context:

-- 1. All of Zaha Hadid's design styles that Max adores have interesting geometries.
--    ∀x, (Zaha x ∧ Adores x) → Interesting x
variable
  (h1 : ∀ x, Zaha x ∧ Adores x → Interesting x)

-- 2. No brutalist buildings that Max adores have interesting geometries.
--    ∀x, (Brutalist x ∧ Adores x) → ¬ Interesting x
variable
  (h2 : ∀ x, Brutalist x ∧ Adores x → ¬ Interesting x)

-- 3. Every style that Max adores is either Zaha Hadid's design style or Kelly Wearstler's design style.
--    We interpret this as: ∀x, Adores x → (Zaha x ∨ Kelly x)
--    (This treats all adored items as falling under the Zaha/Kelly dichotomy.)
variable
  (h3 : ∀ x, Adores x → Zaha x ∨ Kelly x)

-- 4. All of Kelly Wearstler's design styles that Max adores are evocative.
--    ∀x, (Kelly x ∧ Adores x) → Evocative x
variable
  (h4 : ∀ x, Kelly x ∧ Adores x → Evocative x)

-- 5. All of Kelly Wearstler's design styles that Max adores are dreamy.
--    ∀x, (Kelly x ∧ Adores x) → Dreamy x
variable
  (h5 : ∀ x, Kelly x ∧ Adores x → Dreamy x)

-- 6. If a design by Max that he adores has interesting geometries, then the design is a brutalist building and evocative.
--    Interpreted as: ∀x, (Adores x ∧ Interesting x) → (Brutalist x ∧ Evocative x)
variable
  (h6 : ∀ x, Adores x ∧ Interesting x → Brutalist x ∧ Evocative x)

-- Goal (Question): A design by Max is either evocative or dreamy.
-- Interpreted as: ∀x, Adores x → (Evocative x ∨ Dreamy x)
theorem max_designs_evocative_or_dreamy
  : ∀ x, Adores x → (Evocative x ∨ Dreamy x) := by
  intro x hx
  have hz_or_hk : Zaha x ∨ Kelly x := h3 x hx
  cases hz_or_hk with
  | inl hz =>
      -- Zaha-branch: from Zaha ∧ Adores, get Interesting; then from Adores ∧ Interesting, get Evocative.
      have hi : Interesting x := h1 x ⟨hz, hx⟩
      have hbe : Brutalist x ∧ Evocative x := h6 x ⟨hx, hi⟩
      have hev : Evocative x := hbe.right
      exact Or.inl hev
  | inr hk =>
      -- Kelly-branch: from Kelly ∧ Adores, get both Evocative and Dreamy; choose Evocative.
      have hev : Evocative x := h4 x ⟨hk, hx⟩
      -- have hdr : Dreamy x := h5 x ⟨hk, hx⟩
      exact Or.inl hev
</lean>

universe u

constant Entity : Type u

-- Predicates
constant MountainRange : Entity → Prop
constant Mine : Entity → Prop
constant InTexas : Entity → Prop
constant InNewMexico : Entity → Prop
constant LocatedIn : Entity → Entity → Prop
constant Donated : Entity → Prop

-- Constants
constant PicurisMountains : Entity
constant HardingPegmatiteMine : Entity

-- Premises from the text
axiom PM_is_range : MountainRange PicurisMountains
axiom PM_in_NM_or_TX : InNewMexico PicurisMountains ∨ InTexas PicurisMountains
axiom HPM_is_mine : Mine HardingPegmatiteMine
axiom HPM_located_in_PM : LocatedIn HardingPegmatiteMine PicurisMountains
axiom HPM_donated : Donated HardingPegmatiteMine
axiom no_TX_range_with_donated_mine :
  ∀ r : Entity, MountainRange r → InTexas r → ¬ (∃ m : Entity, Mine m ∧ LocatedIn m r ∧ Donated m)

-- Target statement: "The Harding Pegmatite Mine is not located in a mountain range in New Mexico."
def Target : Prop :=
  ¬ (∃ r : Entity, MountainRange r ∧ InNewMexico r ∧ LocatedIn HardingPegmatiteMine r)

-- We prove the negation of the Target (i.e., the statement is false)
theorem not_Target : ¬ Target := by
  -- There exists a donated mine located in Picuris Mountains (namely HPM)
  have ex_donated_mine_in_PM :
      ∃ m : Entity, Mine m ∧ LocatedIn m PicurisMountains ∧ Donated m :=
    ⟨HardingPegmatiteMine,
      And.intro HPM_is_mine (And.intro HPM_located_in_PM HPM_donated)⟩
  -- Therefore, Picuris Mountains cannot be in Texas
  have not_in_TX_PM : ¬ InTexas PicurisMountains := by
    intro htx
    have h := no_TX_range_with_donated_mine PicurisMountains PM_is_range htx
    exact h ex_donated_mine_in_PM
  -- From "in NM or in TX" and "not in TX", deduce "in NM"
  have in_NM_PM : InNewMexico PicurisMountains :=
    PM_in_NM_or_TX.elim (fun hnm => hnm) (fun htx => False.elim (not_in_TX_PM htx))
  -- Exhibit a mountain range in New Mexico that HPM is located in: Picuris Mountains
  have exists_range_in_NM_with_HPM :
      ∃ r : Entity, MountainRange r ∧ InNewMexico r ∧ LocatedIn HardingPegmatiteMine r :=
    ⟨PicurisMountains, And.intro PM_is_range (And.intro in_NM_PM HPM_located_in_PM)⟩
  -- Conclude the negation of Target
  intro hTarget
  exact hTarget exists_range_in_NM_with_HPM
</lean>

constant MostActive : Person → Prop
constant LostToIga : Person → Prop
constant LostToRafa : Person → Prop
constant FemaleRG : Person → Prop
constant MaleRG : Person → Prop

axiom lost_to_iga_implies_ranked_highly : ∀ x, LostToIga x → RankedHighly x
axiom femaleRG_lost_to_iga : ∀ x, FemaleRG x → LostToIga x

axiom maleRG_lost_to_rafa : ∀ x, MaleRG x → LostToRafa x
axiom coco_high_or_rafa_implies_not_male : (RankedHighly Coco ∨ LostToRafa Coco) → ¬ (MaleRG Coco)

  have hrank : RankedHighly Coco := lost_to_iga_implies_ranked_highly Coco hIga
  exact ranked_highly_implies_most_active Coco hrank

end RG2022

constant MaleRG : Person → Prop

axiom ranked_highly_implies_most_active : ∀ x, RankedHighly x → MostActive x
axiom lost_to_iga_implies_ranked_highly : ∀ x, LostToIga x → RankedHighly x

axiom coco_atRG : AtRG Coco

theorem coco_most_active : MostActive Coco := by

  have hfemale : FemaleRG Coco := by
    cases hdisj with

      have hrafa : LostToRafa Coco := maleRG_lost_to_rafa Coco hm
      have hdh : RankedHighly Coco ∨ LostToRafa Coco := Or.inr hrafa
      have hnotmale : ¬ MaleRG Coco := coco_high_or_rafa_implies_not_male hdh

  have hIga : LostToIga Coco := femaleRG_lost_to_iga Coco hfemale
  have hrank : RankedHighly Coco := lost_to_iga_implies_ranked_highly Coco hIga
  exact ranked_highly_implies_most_active Coco hrank

end RG2022

universe u

constant Person : Type u

constant IgaSwiatek : Person
constant RafaelNadal : Person

constant AtRG : Person → Prop                     -- is at Roland Garros 2022
constant Female : Person → Prop                   -- is female
constant Male : Person → Prop                     -- is male
constant LostToIga : Person → Prop                -- lost to Iga Świątek
constant LostToNadal : Person → Prop              -- lost to Rafael Nadal
constant RankedHighWTA : Person → Prop            -- ranked highly by the WTA
constant MostActiveMajor : Person → Prop          -- one of the most active players in major tennis

-- Premises from the text
axiom Prem1 : ∀ x, RankedHighWTA x → MostActiveMajor x
axiom Prem2 : ∀ x, (LostToIga x ∧ AtRG x) → RankedHighWTA x
axiom Prem3 : ∀ x, (Female x ∧ AtRG x) → LostToIga x
axiom Prem4 : ∀ x, AtRG x → (Female x ∨ Male x)
axiom Prem5 : ∀ x, (Male x ∧ AtRG x) → LostToNadal x
axiom Prem6 : (RankedHighWTA CocoGauff ∨ LostToNadal CocoGauff) → ¬ (Male CocoGauff ∧ AtRG CocoGauff)
axiom Prem7 : AtRG CocoGauff

-- Some derivable consequences

-- Either Coco is ranked highly or Coco lost to Nadal (case split on sex at RG).
lemma coco_ranked_or_lostNadal : RankedHighWTA CocoGauff ∨ LostToNadal CocoGauff := by
  have hdisj : Female CocoGauff ∨ Male CocoGauff := Prem4 CocoGauff Prem7

  | inl hF =>
      have hLostIga : LostToIga CocoGauff := Prem3 CocoGauff ⟨hF, Prem7⟩
      exact Or.inl (Prem2 CocoGauff ⟨hLostIga, Prem7⟩)
  | inr hM =>
      exact Or.inr (Prem5 CocoGauff ⟨hM, Prem7⟩)

  Prem6 coco_ranked_or_lostNadal

lemma coco_not_male : ¬ Male CocoGauff := by
  intro hM
  exact coco_not_male_at_RG ⟨hM, Prem7⟩

-- From AtRG and not male, and the dichotomy Female ∨ Male at RG, we get Female.
lemma coco_female : Female CocoGauff := by
  have hdisj : Female CocoGauff ∨ Male CocoGauff := Prem4 CocoGauff Prem7
  cases hdisj with
  | inl hF => exact hF
  | inr hM => exact False.elim (coco_not_male hM)

/- We formalize the problem in Lean 4. -/

constant Person : Type
constant CocoGauff : Person
constant IgaSwiatek : Person
constant RafaelNadal : Person

-- Predicates
constant AtRG : Person → Prop                     -- is at Roland Garros 2022
constant Female : Person → Prop                   -- is female
constant Male : Person → Prop                     -- is male
constant LostToIga : Person → Prop                -- lost to Iga Świątek
constant LostToNadal : Person → Prop              -- lost to Rafael Nadal
constant RankedHighWTA : Person → Prop            -- ranked highly by the WTA
constant MostActiveMajor : Person → Prop          -- one of the most active players in major tennis

-- Premises from the text
axiom Prem1 : ∀ x : Person, RankedHighWTA x → MostActiveMajor x
axiom Prem2 : ∀ x : Person, (LostToIga x ∧ AtRG x) → RankedHighWTA x
axiom Prem3 : ∀ x : Person, (Female x ∧ AtRG x) → LostToIga x
axiom Prem4 : ∀ x : Person, AtRG x → (Female x ∨ Male x)
axiom Prem5 : ∀ x : Person, (Male x ∧ AtRG x) → LostToNadal x
axiom Prem6 : (RankedHighWTA CocoGauff ∨ LostToNadal CocoGauff) → ¬ (Male CocoGauff ∧ AtRG CocoGauff)
axiom Prem7 : AtRG CocoGauff

-- Some derivable consequences

-- Either Coco is ranked highly or Coco lost to Nadal (case split on sex at RG).
lemma coco_ranked_or_lostNadal : RankedHighWTA CocoGauff ∨ LostToNadal CocoGauff := by
  have hdisj : Female CocoGauff ∨ Male CocoGauff := Prem4 CocoGauff Prem7
  cases hdisj with
  | inl hF =>
      have hLostIga : LostToIga CocoGauff := Prem3 CocoGauff ⟨hF, Prem7⟩
      exact Or.inl (Prem2 CocoGauff ⟨hLostIga, Prem7⟩)
  | inr hM =>
      exact Or.inr (Prem5 CocoGauff ⟨hM, Prem7⟩)

  Prem6 coco_ranked_or_lostNadal

  intro hM
  exact coco_not_male_at_RG ⟨hM, Prem7⟩

lemma coco_female : Female CocoGauff := by
  have hdisj : Female CocoGauff ∨ Male CocoGauff := Prem4 CocoGauff Prem7
  cases hdisj with
  | inl hF => exact hF

namespace Reasoning

universe u

constant Person : Type u

constant Michael Peter Windy : Person

constant Man : Person → Prop
constant InMichaelClass : Person → Prop
constant Taller : Person → Person → Prop
constant CanBlock : Person → Person → Prop
constant JumpsWhenShooting : Person → Prop
constant Shooter : Person → Prop
constant GreatShooter : Person → Prop

-- If a man is taller than another man, the taller one can block the other's shooting.
axiom A1 : ∀ {x y : Person}, Man x → Man y → Taller x y → CanBlock x y

-- Michael is a man who is taller than everyone else in his class.
axiom A2 : Man Michael ∧ ∀ y : Person, InMichaelClass y ∧ y ≠ Michael → Taller Michael y

-- Transitivity of taller.
axiom A3 : ∀ {x y z : Person}, Taller x y → Taller y z → Taller x z

-- Peter is a man who is taller than Michael.
axiom A4 : Man Peter ∧ Taller Peter Michael

-- Michael can block any shooting from a person as long as the person does not jump when shooting.
axiom A5 : ∀ x : Person, ¬ JumpsWhenShooting x → CanBlock Michael x

-- Michael cannot block Windy's shooting.
axiom A6 : ¬ CanBlock Michael Windy

-- Every shooter who can jump when shooting is a great shooter.
axiom A7 : ∀ x : Person, Shooter x ∧ JumpsWhenShooting x → GreatShooter x

-- A derived fact: Windy must jump when shooting.
theorem Windy_jumps : JumpsWhenShooting Windy :=
by
  classical
  by_contra h
  have : CanBlock Michael Windy := A5 Windy h
  exact A6 this

-- Target statement: Peter is shorter than a man in Michael's class.
def Target : Prop := ∃ m : Person, Man m ∧ InMichaelClass m ∧ Taller m Peter

-- From the given axioms (which include transitivity but no asymmetry or irreflexivity of Taller),
-- neither Target nor its negation is derivable here.

end Reasoning

constant Person : Type

-- Predicates
constant Man : Person → Prop
constant Taller : Person → Person → Prop
constant CanBlock : Person → Person → Prop
constant JumpWhenShooting : Person → Prop
constant Shooter : Person → Prop
constant GreatShooter : Person → Prop

-- Individuals
constant Michael : Person
constant Peter : Person
constant Windy : Person

-- Assumptions from the text
axiom Taller_man_blocks :
  ∀ x y : Person, Man x → Man y → Taller x y → CanBlock x y

axiom Michael_is_man : Man Michael

axiom taller_trans :
  ∀ x y z : Person, Taller x y → Taller y z → Taller x z

axiom Peter_is_man : Man Peter
axiom Peter_taller_than_Michael : Taller Peter Michael

axiom Michael_blocks_if_no_jump :
  ∀ p : Person, ¬ JumpWhenShooting p → CanBlock Michael p

axiom Michael_cannot_block_Windy :
  ¬ CanBlock Michael Windy

axiom great_if_can_jump :
  ∀ p : Person, Shooter p → JumpWhenShooting p → GreatShooter p

axiom Windy_is_shooter : Shooter Windy

theorem Windy_is_great_shooter : GreatShooter Windy :=
  let hJump : JumpWhenShooting Windy :=
    Or.elim (Classical.em (JumpWhenShooting Windy))
      (fun hj => hj)
      (fun hNot =>
        False.elim (Michael_cannot_block_Windy (Michael_blocks_if_no_jump Windy hNot)))
  great_if_can_jump Windy Windy_is_shooter hJump

-- Entities
constant Person : Type u
constant Michael : Person
constant Peter : Person
constant Windy : Person

-- Predicates/Relations
constant Man : Person → Prop
constant Taller : Person → Person → Prop
constant CanBlock : Person → Person → Prop
constant JumpsWhenShooting : Person → Prop
constant GreatShooter : Person → Prop
constant InMichaelsClass : Person → Prop

-- Axioms from the textual context

-- 1. If a man is taller than another man, the taller one can block the other's shooting.
axiom A1 : ∀ {x y : Person}, Man x → Man y → Taller x y → CanBlock x y

-- 2. Michael is a man who is taller than everyone else in his class.
axiom A2_manMichael : Man Michael
axiom A2_tallerClass : ∀ {y : Person}, InMichaelsClass y → Taller Michael y

-- 3. Transitivity of taller: if x>y and y>z then x>z.
axiom A3_transTaller : ∀ {x y z : Person}, Taller x y → Taller y z → Taller x z

-- 4. Peter is a man who is taller than Michael.
axiom A4_manPeter : Man Peter
axiom A4_taller : Taller Peter Michael

-- 5. Michael can block any shooting from a person as long as the person does not jump when shooting.
axiom A5_M_block_nonjump : ∀ {p : Person}, ¬ JumpsWhenShooting p → CanBlock Michael p

-- 6. Michael cannot block Windy's shooting.
axiom A6_M_cannot_block_Windy : ¬ CanBlock Michael Windy

-- 7. Every shooter who can jump when shooting is a great shooter.
axiom A7_jumpers_great : ∀ {s : Person}, JumpsWhenShooting s → GreatShooter s

-- Some derivable facts (do not settle the main question)

-- From (5) and (6), we can derive ¬¬(Windy jumps when shooting).
lemma windy_double_neg_jumps : ¬¬ JumpsWhenShooting Windy := by
  intro hnot
  have hblock : CanBlock Michael Windy := A5_M_block_nonjump hnot
  exact A6_M_cannot_block_Windy hblock

-- (not provided by the problem): if Windy is a man and in Michael's class.

  (hWman : Man Windy) (hWclass : InMichaelsClass Windy) : CanBlock Peter Windy := by
  have hM_W : Taller Michael Windy := A2_tallerClass hWclass
  have hP_W : Taller Peter Windy := A3_transTaller A4_taller hM_W
  exact A1 A4_manPeter hWman hP_W
